00:09:49.780 --> 00:09:56.020
they are I think of them as containers. They contain data hierarchically, so it's sort

00:09:56.020 --> 00:10:03.020
of a way to describe a tree. The big difference is that the HTML tags or elements are defined

00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:08.440
by a standard, the HTML5 standard is the most recent one, and there's a closed set of tags

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:12.780
and closed set of behaviours for those tags. React components are different because you

00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:17.340
can define your own tags or components with their own behaviours that are specific to

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:23.780
your library or application. They contain something called props. You'll see this term

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:29.820
in React documentation. Props are basically a mapping or a named list of keys to values,

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:34.099
and then they can also contain other components, again, because they're hierarchical, and applications

00:10:34.099 --> 00:10:40.140
are formed by composing these into a tree of some kind. And then once you finish composing

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:44.859
your components, it's React's responsibility to take this user interface that you've described

00:10:44.859 --> 00:10:51.159
using React components and to display it efficiently in the browser.

