Yeah. Would there be any limitations on the React components as to compatibility? For

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:45.119
example, something that does too much in React that you wouldn't be able to support?

00:20:45.119 --> 00:20:50.160
Excellent question. Yes. So we made some cuts there, again, in the interest of ease of use.

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:55.439
There are certain things you can do in React that don't really follow from the model that

00:20:55.439 --> 00:21:01.359
we advocate. We settle on the model we have because it's a set of conventions for interopting

00:21:01.359 --> 00:21:06.280
with React that seem to work for a majority of libraries. There are those edge cases,

00:21:06.280 --> 00:21:10.520
and when you hit the edge cases, it's kind of like the crosstalk story. You need to know

00:21:10.520 --> 00:21:14.880
JavaScript then at that point. But again, when you do get to that point, our goal is

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:20.260
to at least have examples and documentation to support you as you go that direction in

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:26.260
JavaScript world so that it's never totally inaccessible to you, that you identify while

00:21:26.260 --> 00:21:29.260
you're building your widget that that's a step, a bridge you need to cross, and we're

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:31.900
there to hold your hand at least while you do that.

